<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Yesterday we did OPVL together. Today you extend it to a real peer-reviewed scientific paper.</p>
  <p>The hardest OPVL move is naming a <strong>specific Limitation</strong> — not "this source might be biased" but "this source is funded by the company whose product it studies, which means its data on side effects is unlikely to be complete." That specificity is what the rubric's T/T strand is built to detect. Today is where you start building it — on a harder source than a news article.</p>
  <p>Today's anchor source is a 1965 <em>Nature</em> paper by James Lovelock: <strong>"A physical basis for life detection experiments."</strong> In one short paper Lovelock argued that the way to detect life on another planet is to read its atmosphere — an atmosphere held far from chemical equilibrium is a signature of life. That's a beautiful hook into the whole year: the question <em>"how would we recognize life elsewhere?"</em> is the same question as <em>"what makes Earth habitable?"</em>, asked from the other side. You'll meet this exact idea again in <a href="/units/unit-1/">Unit 1</a> when you build a habitability framework for the Goldilocks Report. The reading is assigned the night before as a structured pre-read, so class time is spent on OPVL, not on first-contact with a dense paper.</p>
  <p>Two reasons the article is shared, not individual: in <a href="/units/unit-0/block-3/">Block 3 tomorrow</a> we OPVL an <em>AI summary of this same paper</em> — same content, different source type, different Limitations, and that side-by-side is the point. And Lovelock returns in <a href="/units/unit-1/block-1/">Unit 1 Block 1</a> as the bridge into habitability. The OPVL you do today is not disposable.</p>
  <p>There's also a sub-move today: telling the difference between an <strong>observation</strong>, an <strong>inference</strong>, a <strong>claim</strong>, and an <strong>opinion</strong>. A 1965 thought-experiment paper mixes all four. OPVL on Value and Limitations gets sharper when you can label which is which.</p>
</section>

