<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">🛠️ Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths converge on the same artifact: a full OPVL on Lovelock with a specific Limitation. The path you pick is about how you spend the work time.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can apply OPVL to a peer-reviewed scientific paper, using sentence stems and a structured template, and name at least one Limitation specific to <em>this</em> paper — not generic to all old sources.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">OPVL Lovelock in full (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Using the structured OPVL template, complete Value + Limitations on Lovelock with a partner (Origin + Purpose were modeled as a class). The Limitation must be specific to this paper — e.g., "pre-Viking 1976, so essentially no Mars surface data," or "a single-author thought experiment with no quantitative model" — not "it's old." Carry this OPVL to Block 3 to compare against an AI summary tomorrow.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Lovelock + the Thompson 2022 bridge (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">OPVL Lovelock, then preview <strong>Thompson et al. (2022)</strong> — the modern paper that operationalizes Lovelock's idea with photochemical modeling for methane on a planet JWST can actually observe. Same thesis, 57 years apart, with far more data behind it. One sentence: what does Thompson's Value have that Lovelock's doesn't, and why?</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Student-found article (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If your Source Dossier topic is already mostly chosen, OPVL a source you've found for the dossier instead. Same OPVL structure; same specific-Limitation bar. You'll still see the Lovelock OPVL in Block 3 — Path C is the option for students working ahead.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help with the framework (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Pair up at the peer-help table. Use Lovelock as the shared reference and work OPVL letter-by-letter with a partner and the sentence stems. Mr. Ignash floats; the OPVL framework handout is the anchor.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Pre-teach vocabulary (5 terms)</div>
    <p>The Lovelock pre-read uses five terms worth previewing: <strong>biosignature · thermodynamic equilibrium · entropy · photolysis · phenomenological</strong>. Definitions, visual cues, and sentence stems are on the <a href="/foundations/eal/u0/">U0 EAL Pre-Teach</a> reference + the Block 2 vocabulary handout in Google Classroom.</p>
